  footnotes: []
english:
  title: On the Ninth Month of the Year Muin, Arriving at Tongzhou and Writing a Poem at Chongseok Pavilion
  author: Jung Jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Heaven and earth, as if cast in a forge, have shaped stone into peaks,
    Where distance blurs in the thick mist of smoke and haze.
    Beneath the lowered sky, thousand-foot cliffs stand crimson and bare,
    And wind rises, layering ten thousand acres of green waves.
    In the grass lies a moss-worn monument where dragons once dwelled,
    While cranes cry out from pines that cling to the rocky shore.
    I lean and stand long, as if the world falls away,
    Yet how many times in a lifetime does one encounter such grandeur?
    Occasionally I meet a mountain monk who loves what is ancient and obscure,
    We wander seeking wonders, following one another in pursuit.
    But where have the goddesses in feathered robes gone?
    Through ten thousand clouds I search, yet leave no trace.
  footnotes:
    - Tongzhou (通州) refers to a region in what is now North Korea, a place of scenic beauty along water routes.
    - Chongseok Pavilion (叢石亭) literally means 'Pavilion of Clustered Stones,' a real landmark known for its dramatic rock formations.
    - The feathered-robed goddesses (羽衣) reference Daoist immortals, evoking themes of transcendence and the transient nature of spiritual encounters.
    - The moss-worn dragon (莓龍) is a poetic image suggesting the passage of time and the erosion of worldly things by nature.
